title: For Sale:  Hi Point 9C 9mm NEAR NEW + Holster + 4 magazines
location: Twin Cities Metro, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
I bought this gun a month ago.  I ended up getting a different 9MM so I don't need this anymore.  I have shot one box of winchester out of it.  The magazines are brand new and the springs are extremely stiff.  This causes the first round to nosedive and get stuck. The gun will jam with a full magazine, but if you load it with one less round it works much better.  This gun hasn't jammed AFTER the first round, but just doing dry runs it would jam on the first shot with a fully loaded magazines 50/50. Some people online cut the magazine spring since its so stiff.  This isn't a gun issue, its a magazine issue.  Also this could have been because I was using hollow points. I have a hi point .45 and have had none of these issues.  This gun is stupid accurate. Basically I don't have time for it and am interested in getting rid of it.

It was bought 2/13/2014.  It comes with:
Gun
New Holster
Kydex 'holster' with hardware (for attaching the gun to the bottom of a wood desk or work bench)
3 x 10 round magazines
1 x 8 round magazines
1 x Safety Lock
1 x Ghost Ring Sight

The magazine safety was removed but is included. They put it in for certain state compliance but having it means if you drop the mag on accident you can't fire the round chambered.  

Sorry no trades.  I do western union money orders and ship to FFL only.  Local cash buyers I am willing to meet.

title: For Sale:  M1 Garand
postcontent:
Up for grabs is my "made in America" ! 

My serial number was produced in April 1939. Overwhelming odds are that this rifle saw active duty in WWII due to the high demand in those early years. Think about it... my serial number is 1**40 and troops were not fully issued until serial number 400,000+

Here is the reason it is stamped CAI:

1. America left a lot of firearms in foreign countries after WWII.
2. The gun control act of 1968 gave the ATF power to regulate imports.
3. ATF then started requiring all firearms entering America to be stamped by the importer. This included American arms "returning' to our country.
4. So your serial number and "CAI" stamp simply means that the rifle left the country prior to 1968 and returned after that. A virtual guarantee that it saw active duty in at least one and possibly several wars.



I have 5 upper end contractor clips, and 5 mil spec 8rnd clips. I have recently added a Korean War Issue GI web sling to it as well.

and 80 or so .30-06 rounds from various manufacturers. I also have 60-80 empty re-loadable brass cases.

title: For Sale:  Use an Attorney to Establish a Gun Trust and Protect Your Firearms Legacy
postcontent:
The Rogers Law Group is a Middle Tennessee law firm that is committed to the protection of gun owner rights and other civil liberties.  To that end, our firm offers comprehensive gun trust services for gun owners throughout the region and State.

A gun trust is a way by which you can protect your firearms.  Transferring your firearms through a will exposes the entire world to what firearms you own and who is to receive them, in addition, if the person to whom you will your firearms to is disqualified from possessing a firearm, your guns are seized by the ATF.

A trust eliminates this problem, and many others by ensuring that only you, the executor of the trust and your beneficiaries know who receives your firearms.  Additionally, if phrased properly (and it will be) your firearms can be ensured to transfer for future generations (even those who will be born after your passing).  A trust also allows all named beneficiaries to use and possess your firearms, which, without, could be in violation of the law and incur heavy penalties.

Please contact the Rogers Law Group today to discuss how we can assist you in protecting your firearms and keep them out of the government's hands.  Thank you and we look forward to assisting you soon.

title: For Trade:  MAS MLE 49/56 G series in 7.5x54 French
postcontent: This is a MAS MLE 1949/56 rifle with a G prefix to the serial number dating the rifle between 1958-1960 made at the Saint-Etienne armory.  The Fusil Semi-Automatique de 7.5mm modele 1949/56 or Mas 49/56 is the final variant that started with the Mas 40 though the Mas 40 saw very limited use because of the German occupation of France.  Then after the liberation of France from Nazi forces the variant was updated to the Mas 44 but again saw only limited use until 1949 where the final variant of the action was designed and designated the Mas 1949, of only 20,000 were produced.  7 years later in 1956 the barrel was shortened and forward grenade launching sight was added making the Mas 49/56 of which nearly 275,000 rifles were produced.  The Mas 49/56 was one of the last main issue battle rifles of a bygone era of weapons designs.  Basically the French equivalent to the FAL this robust and reliable tilting bolt direct impingement rifle chambers for the powerful 7.5x54 French even though France was part of NATO they were quite stubborn about using their own ammunition instead of NATO standard.  Most of these rifles were imported by C.A.I. in the 90's after they were removed from French reserve arsenals.  After importing them Century converted most of these rifles to 7.62x51 NATO standard since they thought it would appeal more to American shooters, but they did not modify the gas tube or the bolt to handle the higher pressure .308 cartridge resulting in one of the most commonly ruined rifle on the U.S. market.  Most of the .308 conversions are considered unsafe to fire.  Which is what makes this rifle very nice is that it was left in the original caliber meaning it retains its immaculate machining quality.  These rifles were used extensively and every 10 years or so the rifles in good enough condition were sent back to the armory to be rearsenaled, this rifle has two rearsenal marks, one from 1971 and one from 1981.  During it's second refurbish it's barrel was replaced as indicated by the fact that the barrel is dated 1976.  After its second refurbish I am lead to believe it was never re issued and simply sat in an arsenal for a while.  The man I bought it from bought it from Century with 2 others and he never fired it and neither have I so it is likely a round has never been fired through the barrel (it is absolutely perfect).  The rifle is mechanically perfect and functions flawlessly.  The stock is refinished from the medium quality military finish to a high quality urethane finish.  Comes with a rubber grenade launching boot dated 1962, and 1 10 round magazine.  I am not particularly looking to get rid of the rifle since I like it so much but I am more of a collector of Warsaw Pact and Combloc firearms so I am interested in seeing what else is out there and will trade it for the right deal.
